&gt; <br>
&gt; As defined in Section 3 of [RFC9847], the value N indicates<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 That the item has not been evaluated by the IETF a=
nd that the IETF<br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 has made no statement about the suitability of the=
 associated<br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 mechanism.=C2=A0 This does not necessarily mean th=
at the mechanism is<br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 flawed, only that no consensus exists.=C2=A0 The I=
ETF might have<br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 consensus to leave an item marked as &quot;N&quot;=
 on the basis of the item<br>
&gt;=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 having limited applicability or usage constraints<=
br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; 2. Randomness requirements<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Jacob Appelbaum raised the issue that m random input value is provided=
<br>
&gt; directly to the ML-KEM.Encaps() and encrypted and sent to the TLS<br>
&gt; Client. This means that an attacker who can use raw random output to<b=
r>
&gt; determine the PRNG state can use a connection with the server to<br>
&gt; attempt to derive the server&#39;s PRNG state and attack other<br>
&gt; connections.<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; This issue pertains to the ML-KEM algorithm itself and is not unique<b=
r>
&gt; to TLS. The NIST document currently does require a secure PRNG defined=
<br>
&gt; in NIST SP 800-90A-C and RFC 9846 discusses PRNGs in Appendix C. Any<b=
r>
&gt; text added to address this point would need to be included both in<br>
&gt; this document and the ECDHE-MLKEM document.<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Text to go into Section 4.2, after the existing &quot;MUST NOT reuse<b=
r>
&gt; randomness&quot; line:<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; =E2=80=9CDuring encapsulation, ML-KEM encrypts m, drawn from a random =
bit<br>
&gt; generator, so the peer holding the decapsulation key recovers m<br>
&gt; exactly. Any information that m provides about other outputs of the<br=
>
&gt; generator is therefore available to that peer.=E2=80=9D<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; And the following text for Section 5 (security considerations):<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; =E2=80=9CThe disclosure of raw random number generator (PRNG) output i=
n TLS<br>
&gt; and other protocols can be used in an attack to compromise the state<b=
r>
&gt; of an insecure RNG as described in [DUALEC-TLS]. The m value in ML-KEM=
<br>
&gt; is an additional place where raw RNG output is disclosed to an active<=
br>
&gt; attacker.=C2=A0 Because the m value in ML-KEM is randomly generated an=
d<br>
&gt; transmitted to the client, it is important to follow the PRNG guidance=
<br>
&gt; in [FIPS203] and [RFC9846]. Implementers MAY choose to implement<br>
&gt; mechanisms from [RFC8937] for additional protection across sessions.&q=
uot;<br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; [DUALECTLS] - <a href=3D"https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conferenc=
e/usenixsecurity14/sec14-paper-checkoway.pdf" rel=3D"noreferrer" target=3D"=
_blank">https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conference/usenixsecurity14/sec=
14-paper-checkoway.pdf</a><br>
